  "prompt": "What do the vacuoles in animal cells do?",
  "response": "In animal cells, vacuoles serve several important functions, though they are typically smaller and less prominent compared to plant cell vacuoles:\n\n1. Storage\n- Store water, nutrients, and waste products\n- Can hold ions, proteins, and other cellular materials\n\n2. Waste management\n- Collect and temporarily store cellular waste\n- Help isolate potentially harmful substances from other cell components\n\n3. Maintaining cell shape and structural support\n- Contribute to cell volume and turgor pressure\n- Help maintain cell shape and integrity\n\n4. Cellular digestion\n- Some specialized vacuoles called lysosomes break down cellular debris and foreign materials\n- Contain enzymes that can digest proteins, lipids, and other molecules\n\n5. pH regulation\n- Help maintain proper pH balance within the cell\n- Can store and regulate concentration of various substances\n\nWhile animal cell vacuoles are less significant compared to plant cell vacuoles, they still play crucial roles in cellular function and maintenance.",
